[
  {
    "page": 1,
    "title": "How To Recover After Emergency Tooth Extractions?",
    "article": "\n<img alt=\"How To Recover After Emergency Tooth Extractions?_1\" class=\"old_img\" data-smallsrc=\"//cdn.uslowcostdental.com/Images/content_small/how-to-recover-after-emergency-tooth-extractions/how-to-recover-after-emergency-tooth-extractions_1.jpg\" data-src=\"//cdn.uslowcostdental.com/Images/content/how-to-recover-after-emergency-tooth-extractions/how-to-recover-after-emergency-tooth-extractions_1.jpg\" data-webpsmallsrc=\"//cdn.uslowcostdental.com/Images/content_small/how-to-recover-after-emergency-tooth-extractions/how-to-recover-after-emergency-tooth-extractions_1.webp\" data-webpsrc=\"//cdn.uslowcostdental.com/Images/content/how-to-recover-after-emergency-tooth-extractions/how-to-recover-after-emergency-tooth-extractions_1.webp\" lazyload=\"\" src=\"/Public/Images/load.png\">\n<p>Taking care of your teeth after an emergency tooth extraction is important for healing and feeling better. This guide gives you important information on what to do after the extraction, so that you can recover smoothly and minimize any discomfort.</p>\n</img>"
  },
  {
    "page": 2,
    "title": "How To Recover After Emergency Tooth Extractions?",
    "article": "\n<h4>1. What To Do Immediately After the Extraction</h4>\n<img alt=\"How To Recover After Emergency Tooth Extractions?_2\" class=\"old_img\" data-smallsrc=\"//cdn.uslowcostdental.com/Images/content_small/how-to-recover-after-emergency-tooth-extractions/how-to-recover-after-emergency-tooth-extractions_2.jpg\" data-src=\"//cdn.uslowcostdental.com/Images/content/how-to-recover-after-emergency-tooth-extractions/how-to-recover-after-emergency-tooth-extractions_2.jpg\" data-webpsmallsrc=\"//cdn.uslowcostdental.com/Images/content_small/how-to-recover-after-emergency-tooth-extractions/how-to-recover-after-emergency-tooth-extractions_2.webp\" data-webpsrc=\"//cdn.uslowcostdental.com/Images/content/how-to-recover-after-emergency-tooth-extractions/how-to-recover-after-emergency-tooth-extractions_2.webp\" lazyload=\"\" src=\"/Public/Images/load.png\">\n<p>Once your tooth is extracted, the dentist will provide a gauze pad for you to bite down on, helping to stop the bleeding. It's important to keep the gauze in place and apply gentle pressure for the time recommended by your dentist. Rest and avoid any strenuous activities for the next 24 hours.</p>\n</img>"
  },
  {
    "page": 3,
    "title": "How To Recover After Emergency Tooth Extractions?",
    "article": "\n<h4>2. Managing Pain And Swelling</h4>\n<img alt=\"How To Recover After Emergency Tooth Extractions?_3\" class=\"old_img\" data-smallsrc=\"//cdn.uslowcostdental.com/Images/content_small/how-to-recover-after-emergency-tooth-extractions/how-to-recover-after-emergency-tooth-extractions_3.jpg\" data-src=\"//cdn.uslowcostdental.com/Images/content/how-to-recover-after-emergency-tooth-extractions/how-to-recover-after-emergency-tooth-extractions_3.jpg\" data-webpsmallsrc=\"//cdn.uslowcostdental.com/Images/content_small/how-to-recover-after-emergency-tooth-extractions/how-to-recover-after-emergency-tooth-extractions_3.webp\" data-webpsrc=\"//cdn.uslowcostdental.com/Images/content/how-to-recover-after-emergency-tooth-extractions/how-to-recover-after-emergency-tooth-extractions_3.webp\" lazyload=\"\" src=\"/Public/Images/load.png\">\n<p>Pain and swelling are common after an extraction. Your dentist might prescribe painkillers or recommend over-the-counter options. You can also place a cold pack on your cheek for 10-20 minutes at a time.</p>\n</img>"
  },
  {
    "page": 4,
    "title": "How To Recover After Emergency Tooth Extractions?",
    "article": "\n<h4>3. Eating And Drinking Post-Extraction</h4>\n<img alt=\"How To Recover After Emergency Tooth Extractions?_4\" class=\"old_img\" data-smallsrc=\"//cdn.uslowcostdental.com/Images/content_small/how-to-recover-after-emergency-tooth-extractions/how-to-recover-after-emergency-tooth-extractions_4.jpg\" data-src=\"//cdn.uslowcostdental.com/Images/content/how-to-recover-after-emergency-tooth-extractions/how-to-recover-after-emergency-tooth-extractions_4.jpg\" data-webpsmallsrc=\"//cdn.uslowcostdental.com/Images/content_small/how-to-recover-after-emergency-tooth-extractions/how-to-recover-after-emergency-tooth-extractions_4.webp\" data-webpsrc=\"//cdn.uslowcostdental.com/Images/content/how-to-recover-after-emergency-tooth-extractions/how-to-recover-after-emergency-tooth-extractions_4.webp\" lazyload=\"\" src=\"/Public/Images/load.png\">\n<p>After your extraction, stick to soft foods and liquids. Don't use a straw for the first 24 hours because it can disturb the healing clot. As your mouth gets better, you can slowly start eating more solid foods again.</p>\n</img>"
  },
  {
    "page": 5,
    "title": "How To Recover After Emergency Tooth Extractions?",
    "article": "\n<h4>4. Oral Hygiene And Wound Care</h4>\n<img alt=\"How To Recover After Emergency Tooth Extractions?_5\" class=\"old_img\" data-smallsrc=\"//cdn.uslowcostdental.com/Images/content_small/how-to-recover-after-emergency-tooth-extractions/how-to-recover-after-emergency-tooth-extractions_5.jpg\" data-src=\"//cdn.uslowcostdental.com/Images/content/how-to-recover-after-emergency-tooth-extractions/how-to-recover-after-emergency-tooth-extractions_5.jpg\" data-webpsmallsrc=\"//cdn.uslowcostdental.com/Images/content_small/how-to-recover-after-emergency-tooth-extractions/how-to-recover-after-emergency-tooth-extractions_5.webp\" data-webpsrc=\"//cdn.uslowcostdental.com/Images/content/how-to-recover-after-emergency-tooth-extractions/how-to-recover-after-emergency-tooth-extractions_5.webp\" lazyload=\"\" src=\"/Public/Images/load.png\">\n<p>Keeping your mouth clean is important. After 24 hours, rinse gently with warm salt water to clean the extraction area, especially after eating. Remember to brush and floss your other teeth as usual, but be cautious around the extraction site.</p>\n</img>"
  },
  {
    "page": 6,
    "title": "How To Recover After Emergency Tooth Extractions?",
    "article": "\n<h4>5. Watching For Complications</h4>\n<img alt=\"How To Recover After Emergency Tooth Extractions?_6\" class=\"old_img\" data-smallsrc=\"//cdn.uslowcostdental.com/Images/content_small/how-to-recover-after-emergency-tooth-extractions/how-to-recover-after-emergency-tooth-extractions_6.jpg\" data-src=\"//cdn.uslowcostdental.com/Images/content/how-to-recover-after-emergency-tooth-extractions/how-to-recover-after-emergency-tooth-extractions_6.jpg\" data-webpsmallsrc=\"//cdn.uslowcostdental.com/Images/content_small/how-to-recover-after-emergency-tooth-extractions/how-to-recover-after-emergency-tooth-extractions_6.webp\" data-webpsrc=\"//cdn.uslowcostdental.com/Images/content/how-to-recover-after-emergency-tooth-extractions/how-to-recover-after-emergency-tooth-extractions_6.webp\" lazyload=\"\" src=\"/Public/Images/load.png\">\n<p>Be watchful for signs of infection or dry socket. Dry socket occurs when the blood clot in the extraction site comes loose. Symptoms to watch out for include intense pain, bad taste, fever, or excessive swelling. If you notice any of these signs, contact your dentist immediately.</p>\n</img>"
  }
]